# Papers -> Research Notes

When a PDF is added to `papers/`, parse it end-to-end and produce two artifacts.

## 1. Per-paper note: `notes/papers/<author-year-slug>.md`
Read the full paper and fill this template. Be specific and quote key numbers/effect sizes.

```markdown
# <Title>

- **Authors / Year**: 
- **Venue / Source**: 
- **PDF**: ../../papers/<file>.pdf
- **Themes**: [[jobs]], [[working-hours]], ...  # link to notes/concepts/

## Research question(s)
- 

## Methodology
- Design (causal/descriptive/structural), identification strategy, model.

## Data
- Source, sample, unit of observation, time period, key variables.

## Main results
- Headline findings with magnitudes and uncertainty.

## Relevance to AI economic impact
- How this informs jobs / hours / sectors / wages / productivity.

## Limitations & open questions
- 
```

## 2. Concept note(s): `notes/concepts/<concept>.md`
After summarizing, create or update a thematic note tied to the economic impact of AI
(e.g. `jobs.md`, `working-hours.md`, `by-sector.md`, `wages.md`, `productivity.md`).

```markdown
# <Concept> (e.g. Impact on Jobs)

## Summary
- Current synthesis across papers.

## Evidence
- <Finding> - [<Author Year>](../papers/<slug>.md)

## Tensions / disagreements
- 

## Open questions
- 
```

## Rules
- Always cross-link: paper notes reference concept notes and vice versa.
- One concept per concept-note; split when a theme grows too broad.
- Do not edit raw PDFs in `papers/`; they are input only.
- Slugs are lowercase, hyphenated (e.g. `acemoglu-2024-automation`).
